tivities. With lucid prose, Jiménez reveals how immigration not only changes the American cityscape but also reshapes the United States by altering the outlooks and identities of its most established citizens.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 4adaca. 4aestablished citizens. 4aestablished immigrants. 4ahuman rights advocate. 4aimmigrant-rich environment. 4aimmigration studies. 4ainfluence of immigrants. 4anationalism. 4apolitical science major. 4asilicon valley. 4aus immigrant relations. 4axenophobia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2017z978311066755408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520968370423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520968370.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066755-4  UC Press eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles